<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUN 92 / International Company News: French public-sector chiefs face
review
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM DAWKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE French cabinet is today expected to decide the fate of the chairmen of a
number of leading state-owned companies as their three-year mandates come up
for review.
Very few of them are expected to lose their jobs, with the notable exception
of the chairman of Bull, the loss-making computer group. The government
yesterday announced that Mr Bernard Pache, the chairman of Charbonnages de
France, would succeed Mr Francis Lorentz as Bull's chief.
The government wants to ensure management continuity where possible. It
needs to avoid worrying other shareholders while it is selling minority
stakes in state companies to fund its employment policies. It also needs to
be cautious because many state-controlled groups are forging alliances with
foreign partners.
Mr Alain Gomez, chairman of Thomson, the civil and defence electronics group
since 1982, was yesterday proposed for re-selection by his board, putting an
end to recent speculation over his future.
During his tenure, Mr Gomez has trimmed Thomson's activities from 23
disparate businesses to three core businesses - defence systems, home
audio-visual products and semiconductors. He also launched a series of
ambitious international acquisitions. Thomson is currently attempting to
take over the missiles division of LTV, the US steel and industrial group,
against intense political resistance in the US.
Confirmation of Mr Gomez's reappointment by the cabinet should be automatic,
making him one of the longest-serving state industry chiefs and one of the
few to keep his job since the round of nationalisations 10 years ago.
The government is also expected to reappoint Mr Loik Le Floch-Prigent,
chairman of Elf-Aquitaine; Mr Jean Gandois, chairman of Pechiney, the
aluminium and packaging group; and Mr Bernard Attali, chairman of Air
France, who has already been proposed by his own board. Other nominations
expected include the top jobs at the banks Credit Lyonnais, Banque Hervet,
Compagnie Financiere du CIC, Union Europeene and Societe Marseillaise de
Credit.
</TEXT>
