<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUN 92 / UK Company News: Whitecroft falls 27% to Pounds 4.49m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN HAMILTON FAZEY, Northern Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WHITECROFT, the Cheshire-based group which last week announced a sharp cut
in dividend to dampen expectations ahead of its results, yesterday reported
a 27 per cent drop in pre-tax profits before exceptional items to Pounds
4.49m for the year to end-March, with operating profits halved.
The group is undergoing a painful reconstruction. It is still disengaging
from property but has largely completed reorganisation of its lighting,
building products, medical cotton fibre and textiles businesses, with cost
savings now likely.
The final dividend wascut to 0.7p, making 4p for the year compared with 10p
in 1990-91. Earnings were 5.65p (4.26p)
Turnover was down 10 per cent at Pounds 129.19m (Pounds 143.13m). Operating
profit was Pounds 4.72m. After interest of Pounds 228,000, pre-tax profits
were Pounds 4.49m. Accounts for the previous year were restated to reflect
different treatment of reorganisation costs. Operating profits in fiscal
1991 were Pounds 9.45m, the exceptional charge Pounds 3.3m and interest
Pounds 3.33m giving pre-tax profits of Pounds 2.81m.
Whitecroft took an extraordinary charge of Pounds 6.27m (Pounds 5.05m) in
the latest period, relating mainly to its withdrawal from property
development. The retained loss for the year was Pounds 5.69m (loss of Pounds
6.98m a year earlier).
The group sold its housebuilding division in January, reducing borrowings by
Pounds 6m but year-end gearing was still 78 per cent on shareholders' funds
of Pounds 45m.
Ongoing sales of houses it retained is expected to bring in Pounds 4m, with
another Pounds 800,000 of deferred consideration to come.
Mr Peter Goold chairman, said all construction was completed and several
lettings had now been achieved.
The biggest single development is a complex of shops and offices in
Sheffield.
</TEXT>
