<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUN 92 / Ferranti shares gain 17% as losses are cut to Pounds 39.6m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANGUS FOSTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FERRANTI International, the electronics and defence group which came close
to collapse following the 1989 discovery of huge fraud in its US subsidiary,
International Signal and Control, yesterday appeared to be back on course
for recovery.
The company announced less severe losses than expected and said three 'life
threatening' litigation claims against a problem US subsidiary, FICC, have
been settled. Ferranti's shares jumped 17 per cent in response, from 8.75p
to 10.25p.
Ferranti reported pre-tax losses of Pounds 39.6m in the year to March 31,
compared with losses of Pounds 98.1m in the previous period. The losses
included Pounds 6.6m from discontinued businesses and exceptional costs of
Pounds 13.9m from rationalisations and fixed asset write-offs.
Mr Eugene Anderson, chairman since 1990, said Ferranti's markets remained
tough, especially given the downturn in defence spending.
'We're getting close to (profits) but the key is winning more business,' he
said.
A disposal programme, which included the sale of its missile business to
GEC, is continuing. Employee numbers fell to just over 5,000 at the start of
this month, compared with about 27,000 in 1989.
Disposals raised Pounds 69.8m and net borrowings fell from Pounds 94.8m to
Pounds 66.5m. But gearing remains close to 100 per cent, and further
disposals are due this year.
Turnover fell nearly a quarter to Pounds 362.6m while turnover on continuing
business was down about 17 per cent. However, the company won Pounds 249.4m
of new business in the defence and civil sectors and the order book at
year-end was Pounds 272.1m.
Litigation stemming from the fraud, which Ferranti estimates cost the
company more than Pounds 600m, is continuing. Mr James Guerin, former
chairman of ISC, was jailed for 15 years earlier this month. Ferranti has
recovered Dollars 1.2m (Pounds 640,000) from proceedings involving another
ISC employee.
About Pounds 41.1m of losses related to the fraud have so far been
recovered. Some Pounds 40m was paid by Peat Marwick, auditor to ISC.
There was a loss per share of 4p, compared with a 11.5p loss a year ago. No
dividend is recommended. Extraordinary losses of Pounds 6.6m on the closure
of businesses took losses for the year to Pounds 44.1m.
Loss reduced, Page 22
