<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUN 92 / Electrolux and AEG set for joint deal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   STOCKHOLM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ELECTROLUX of Sweden, one of the world's leading white goods manufacturers,
is poised to enter an agreement with AEG Hausgerate, a subsidiary of AEG of
Germany, for joint production and development of household appliances.
The deal would initially cover washing machines, tumble dryers and
dishwashers which both companies make. They will continue to compete in the
domestic appliance market under their respective brand names but in the
long-term, they aim to have integrated plants to enable both companies to
lower costs and increase efficiency.
AEG Hausgerate had global sales of DM2.6bn (Pounds 892m) last year and
around 10,300 workers in 16 countries. AEG group itself is 80 per cent owned
by Daimler-Benz with sales last year of DM14bn and 76,000 employees. As well
as household appliances it also produces rail and electrotechnical systems
and components, automation technology and microelectronics.
Under yesterday's proposed agreement, Electrolux will acquire 10 per cent of
the shares in AEG Hausgerate with the option of increasing its holding to 20
per cent.
In return, AEG will subscribe to debentures issued by Electrolux which will
be convertible into ordinary B shares.
Mr Leif Johansson, Electrolux president, said further financial details
would be announced by the end of the year when the deal was completed.
In a joint statement, Mr Anders Scharp, chairman and chief executive of
Electrolux, and Mr Ernst Stockl, chairman of AEG' s board of management,
said: 'To both AEG and Electrolux this arrangement will be strategic as a
means to enable each party to meet the increasing competition from the US
and Japan in the European domestic appliance market.'
For the past two years, Electrolux has been supplying AEG with cold storage
equipment and the experience of the two companies working together hastened
closer co-operation.
Together the two companies account for around 18 per cent of the German
market in the household appliances they both manufacture. The deal has to be
approved by the relevant anti-trust authorities and Electrolux shareholders.
This is expected to happen in the early autumn.
White goods war, Page 26
