FT  24 JUN 92 / Warning on Lasmo US share offering
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
GOLDMAN SACHS, the US investment bank handling the flotation of Ultramar
Corporation, the North American oil refining business owned by Lasmo of the
UK, said last night the price range at which the shares were likely to be
sold had been cut to Dollars 15-Dollars 17.
However, both Goldman and Ultramar, which confirmed the reduction in price
from its Tarrytown, New York State, headquarters, said they still expected
the offering to take place 'one day this week'.
In its original filing with the US Securities and Exchange Commission, dated
May 1, Ultramar Corporation suggested a maximum offering price of Dollars 21
a share. It said it was planning to sell 33m shares, excluding up to 4.95m
shares which might also be sold if over-allotment options granted to
underwriters were exercised.
At the Dollars 21-a-share offering price, the equity offering would have
generated just under Dollars 700m for the British oil and gas company, with
a concurrent offering of debt securities raising a further Dollars 400m. At
the latest Dollars 15-Dollars 17 price, the sum raised from the share
flotation would range between Dollars 495m and Dollars 561m.
Goldman Sachs added yesterday that, aside from the reduced sale price range
for the shares, all other aspects of the offer remained unchanged.
Earlier in the day in London, nervousness about the fate of the
International Public Offer sent Lasmo shares tumbling, making the stock the
worst performer in the FT-SE 100 index. The price fell 15p to 172p - the
lowest level since December 1987 - on heavy trading volume.
In the wake of the aborted GPA flotation, dealers were worried that the
offering might be pulled altogether, or that the price could be cut.
However, dealers seemed to expect the reduced price range would still be
around Dollars 17-Dollars 19.
Lasmo's disposal of the North American downstream assets, earmarked since it
took over Ultramar last year, has been shrouded in uncertainty for some
months.
Analysts have suggested that Lasmo originally hoped a single buyer for the
business would emerge, and only opted for a flotation when a suitable
purchaser failed to materialise.
