<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUN 92 / Demise of clocking-on winds up Rover staff
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TIME WAS when British workers viewed the machine which monitored their
latenesses and absences as a symbol of managerial oppression. But at Rover,
the prospect of an end to clocking-on is winding some workers up.
As part of a 'new deal' on working practices and bargaining procedures, the
company and unions agreed this spring to the phased abolition of
clocking-on. Timekeeping would in future be monitored by production managers
and team leaders.
Now the company has agreed to keep the mechanisms in place in some parts of
its Longbridge plant after protests from workers. 'We are committed to
phasing out clocking-on, but we have said that if workers want to clock on,
they can do,' the company said.
In the areas where the machines remain in place, they will not be used for
calculating pay, as they were before. Rover said the clocking-on machines
would merely be a registration process which team leaders could use if they
wanted.
It is more than just attachment to a decades-old tradition that has endeared
Rover workers to clocking-on. Mr John Allen, an executive councillor of the
Amalgamated Engineering and Electrical Union, said the system provided
'security for an employee and gives proof of attendance'.
Mr Allen said he knew of three recent cases where workers questioned by
police proved their innocence by producing their clocking-on cards. Other
union officials say that workers are concerned about the increased powers
the replacement system would give to team leaders.
Rover is one of a growing number of companies which wants to end clocking-on
for manual workers as part of a move to single-status employment, which also
includes communal canteens and harmonised sick pay for all workers.
However, some companies have harmonised clocking-on systems for all staff.
At the Mars food manufacturing company everyone, including the managing
director, clocks on each morning. A good-timekeeping allowance of 10 per
cent of daily pay is given to employees.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 20
</PAGE>
