<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUN 92 / Post prices frozen to year-end: Record pre-tax profit of
Pounds 247m will not save PO from more competition
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
POSTAGE PRICES for first and second class mail will be frozen until at least
the end of the year as the Post Office announced a record pre-tax profit of
Pounds 247m for the year to March 29.
Sir Bryan Nicholson, chairman, said the Post Office's increased productivity
and cost reductions could make it harder for the government to deregulate
the market - although he made it clear he was not afraid of more
competition.
Sir Bryan said people had put it to him that increasing the Post Office's
profitability had made it harder for potential new competitors to enter a
deregulated market.
Last year the government announced plans to end the Post Office's monopoly
on sending letters priced under Pounds 1.
A government official yesterday said: 'We are still committed to introducing
more competition and will do so in the next parliament, notwithstanding the
Post Office's good results.'
For the first time since the government announced its decision to establish
a national lottery, Sir Bryan revealed that the corporation had made a
formal bid to run the lottery with another company, through its network of
20,000 Post Office counter shops.
This year's Pounds 247m profit compares with a 1990-91 figure of Pounds 153m
before Pounds 106m of exceptional items relating to reorganisation of Royal
Mail, the letters division, and of Parcelforce, the parcels division. Group
turnover for the group increased from Pounds 4.7bn to Pounds 5.1bn.
Royal Mail's profits before tax and exceptional items increased from Pounds
171m to Pounds 266m. Post Office Counters' pre-tax profits fell by Pounds 2m
to Pounds 26m.
Parcelforce continues to lose money. It made a loss of Pounds 24m, before
tax and exceptional items, compared with a Pounds 75m loss in 1990-91. It
shed 550 administrative jobs and closed more of the division's operational
centres in a move designed to make the parcels division break even. Sir
Bryan said he continued to hope that it would make a profit by next year.
Mr Tom Corrigan, chairman of the Post Office Users' National Council, said:
'Parcelforce has lost Pounds 131m in the past two years and had it not been
for the efforts of Royal Mail, the Post Office would clearly have failed to
meet the mandatory financial targets imposed on it by government.'
Sir Bryan's pay increased by 14 per cent from Pounds 149,195 to Pounds
170,471, reflecting performance-related bonuses. The annual accounts also
disclosed that four other Post Office board members were paid between Pounds
135,000 and Pounds 150,000.
The Post Office was again able to waive its contribution to the main
employee pension fund because it was in surplus for the second year running.
</TEXT>
