<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUN 92 / Coke's green bottle takes a fall
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN THORNHILL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
COCA-COLA yesterday launched in Europe its first plastic bottle partly made
from recycled material, but quickly ran into criticism from environmental
groups.
Mr Ralph Cooper, president of the company's European Community Group, said
recycling of plastic into new containers would eventually become as common
as recycling in the glass, aluminium and steel industries.
The bottle, of which 25 per cent is recycled plastic, has been launched into
a limited market covering Shoreham-by-Sea, Brighton and Worthing on the
south coast of England. Consumers will be able to return bottles via
kerbside collection boxes to an experimental materials recovery facility in
West Sussex. The bottles will then be sent to a reprocessing plant in the
US.
The regenerated pure plastic resin will be sent back to existing Coca-Cola
bottling plants in Europe to be included in the normal manufacturing
process.
The two-litre PET (polyethylene terephthalate) bottles are indistinguishable
from other Coca-Cola bottles, apart from a special logo.
Friends of the Earth, the environmental pressure group, said it would have
preferred Coca-Cola to have introduced returnable PET bottles as it had in
the Netherlands. These bottles, which carry a Fl 1 (30p) deposit, are
heavier than the non-refillable PET bottles (110 grammes as opposed to 50
grammes) but can be returned, cleaned and re-used.
Environment, Page 16
