FT  24 JUN 92 / Parliament and Politics: Move on MPs' interests endorsed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NEW PROCEDURES to ensure that MPs elected to the chairmanships of Commons
committees do not have business interests likely to conflict with their
parliamentary duties were backed from both sides of the House last night.
Mr Tony Newton, leader of the House, hinted that the government is likely to
favour arrangements which make it unnecessary to adopt a proposal requiring
committee chairmen to divest themselves of any pecuniary interest which may
be thought to influence their judgment.
He promised to consider the views expressed by MPs in a short debate on a
report by the select committee on Members' interests before reaching any
final decision on how the House should be asked to implement its
recommendations.
Mr Terence Higgins, chairman of the Treasury committee in the last
parliament, agreed that MPs elected to such positions were in a different
position from their colleagues.
While committee chairmen should be subject to more stringent rules on the
disclosure of their outside interests he believed it would be wrong to
insist that they should have none.
To take such a step, it was argued, would be to impose a penalty which was
not imposed on other MPs.
Mr Higgins, who has also served as chairman of the liaison committee which
co-ordinates the work of the Commons committees, maintained that the best
people to judge whether the outside interests of the chairman were likely to
conflict with the work of the select committee were the other members of
that particular committee.
He argued that there was no need for specific requirements to be imposed by
a special resolution of the House.
