FT  24 JUN 92 / GPs end 24-hour cover
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
FAMILY doctors yesterday voted in favour of ending their current commitment
to providing 24-hour cover for patients.
A British Medical Association conference in London supported the replacement
of the general practitioners' existing legal responsibility to provide
full-time cover with more flexible arrangements. The move follows a survey
of GPs earlier this year which showed strong support for the change.
Dr Ian Bogle, chairman of the BMA's general medical services committee, said
the issue concerned how out-of-hours cover should be provided rather than
whether it should continue. Any alternative arrangements introduced would
ensure continuation of home visits when necessary.
The BMA leaders will now have to approach health department ministers for
talks on the introduction of more flexible contracts for GPs.
The government last night pressed ahead with plans for a 7 per cent cut in
dental charges and dentists' fees.
Health Secretary Virginia Bottomley announced that the cut would take effect
from July 8.
