<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUN 92 / Parliament and Politics: Major seeks rapid action to widen
EC
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN MAJOR signalled last night that Britain will press its European
partners to finalise by the end of this year a detailed mandate for
enlargement negotiations with at least four Efta countries.
At a working dinner in Downing Street with Mr Jacques Delors, the European
Commission president, the prime minister also called for the Brussels
executive to speed up the work to define the role of 'subsidiarity' in the
Community's decision-making.
Mr Major, whose talks with Mr Delors focused on this week's Lisbon summit
and the subsequent British presidency of the EC, said he was determined to
put enlargement at the centre of his agenda.
Senior colleagues said he wanted the Commission to draw up over the next few
months the EC's basic negotiating stance with Sweden, Switzerland, Finland,
Austria and, possibly, Norway. The aim would be to translate that into a
firm mandate at December's Edinburgh summit.
Mr Major acknowledges that several other EC governments have been unwilling
to contemplate enlargement until the Maastricht treaty is ratified. But he
appears determined that their objections should not delay preparations.
His government's view is that a commitment to enlargement will be a central
element in a package of measures to allow the Danish government to hold a
second referendum on the treaty.
A second element is a much tighter definition of subsidiarity - ensuring the
Community only has authority in areas where national governments cannot
operate effectively.
Officials said Mr Major welcomed the work that Mr Delors had already
instituted but stressed the need to translate the theory into practical
decisions. That would involve both a review of areas where the Commission
had taken 'unnecessary' powers, and a mechanism to ensure that it did not do
so in the future.
The prime minister sees tangible progress on both fronts as one of his most
potent weapons in efforts to isolate Tory critics of Maastricht, as well as
in the Community's attempts to reassure the Danes.
As ministers brushed off another attack by Tory Euro-sceptics yesterday, Mr
Major underlined his determination not to renege on Maastricht during a
meeting with officers of the influential 1922 committee of backbench MPs.
Mr Douglas Hurd, the foreign secretary, will convey the same message in a
much larger gathering of Conservative MPs later today.
The government will delay the renomination of a second British EC
commissioner until after next month's Labour leadership election. Re-opening
speculation about a possible move to Brussels by Mr Neil Kinnock, Mr Major
agreed to Labour requests that any decision over Mr Bruce Millan's future
should not be taken until after the contest. Sir Leon Brittan will be
reappointed as senior British Commissioner.
</TEXT>
