<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUN 92 / Parliament and Politics: Labour braced for unfraternal
debate - A look at today's meeting about the party's roots
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE anguished debate about Labour's union links, which sputtered into life
after the party's election defeat, looks set to run and run.
The party's national executive is today expected to endorse a review of
those links which will reach a climax at the party conference next year.
Unfortunately for Labour, the possibility of the debate remaining objective
and good-tempered is almost nil. The union link is an emotional issue going
to the heart of what people think the party is for. Further, both wings of
the debate - those who want a complete split and those who want little
change - have powerful arguments on their side.
Supporters of the link argue that without the block vote and the common
sense of union leaders the party would merely reflect the passions of
middle-class constituency activists and be even less electable than it now
is.
The unions give the party roots and cash and are therefore entitled to some
say in its policy forums. If general affiliation was ended, it is argued, it
would produce US-style 'pork-barrel' politics with unions picking and
choosing between parties and politicians.
Supporters of the status quo include influential union leaders such as Mr
Bill Morris, general secretary of the TGWU, the biggest union affiliated to
Labour. Those in favour of a complete break, including at least one Labour
frontbench spokesman, do not deny that the unions have been a stabilising
influence on the party in the past few decades.
Unions, they say, may not be unpopular, but Labour's link with a declining
lobby group for producer interests is unpopular with voters assessing a
potential government.
Supporters of a complete institutional break say Labour and the unions would
continue to share broad policy objectives and values and see no reason why
unions should not go on funding the party.
Union leaders have expressed bitterness at the fact that they are being
blamed for Labour's defeat.
But equally the 'no say, no pay' rhetoric of some union leaders should not
hide the fact that most recognise that a re-ordering of the link is
required.
The GMB general union, like several senior Labour politicians, is attracted
by the idea of 'associate' Labour membership for the 4.5m union members who
pay the political levy - many of them unwittingly.
Such people would become local party members but would have only one third
of the voting power of a full member.
At national level the electoral college, on which the unions now have a 40
per cent vote, would be de-unionised. The block vote at conference would
come down to 50 per cent from the current 90 per cent and would not be cast
as a block. The 12 union seats on the 24-strong national executive - and
reserved union seats on the national policy forum - might also be reduced.
Unlike Mr Neil Kinnock, the outgoing party leader, Mr John Smith - the
favourite to succeed him - does not like doing deals in smoke-filled rooms.
He instinctively supports the widest possible move to one member, one vote
at local level, but he is unlikely to want a complete split. Diluting the
union role by raising the number of interest groups which have a say in
party forums - such as those on local government or consumers - is being
considered. That, however, will hardly improve Labour's chances of speaking
for the general interest.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 11
</PAGE>
