<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUN 92 / Parliament and Politics: Secret services face new scrutiny
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT has indicated that it will consider increasing the scrutiny
of Britain's overseas and domestic intelligence services, Ralph Atkins
writes.
Legislation is already planned to put the Secret Intelligence Service, or
MI6, on a legal basis. But extra clauses to increase the service's
accountability to the Commons were not ruled out by Downing Street
yesterday.
An official at the Foreign Office, which is responsible for MI6, said that
consideration of the bill's contents was at an early stage but, 'it is all
up for grabs'.
Last month, the prime minister confirmed, for the first time, the existence
of MI6 and named its chief, Sir Colin McColl.
The domestic intelligence service, MI5, was put on a statutory basis in 1989
and, theoretically, is accountable to MPs via ministers. It is probable that
any extra scrutiny applied to MI6 would extend to MI5.
Some MPs however are demanding that the intelligence services should be
accountable to a Commons committee, or a committee of privy councillors.
</TEXT>
