<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUN 92 / Capping eased for Tory authorities
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TWO OF the three Tory-controlled councils to have their spending for next
year 'capped', or limited by the government, have had the limits relaxed
slightly, Mr Michael Howard, the environment secretary, announced yesterday.
The budget limit for Basildon has been raised by Pounds 1.95m, and that for
Warwickshire has been increased by Pounds 4m. The third council whose
representations proved at least partly effective was Gloucestershire (which
no one party controls), and whose spending limit has been increased by
Pounds 2.59m.
The cuts now represent a poll tax reduction of Pounds 41 off the Pounds 361
per head in Basildon. In Gloucestershire and Warwickshire, where the tax had
been at levels of between Pounds 290 and Pounds 350, the cuts are Pounds 18
and Pounds 8 per head respectively.
Mr Howard described the caps, or limits, now imposed as 'reasonable,
appropriate and achievable in all the circumstances of the authorities
concerned'. Five of the other seven councils whose budgets were capped had
appeals against the original limits rejected. They will have three weeks to
set new budgets.
The capping limits will be debated by MPs today. Some MPs will welcome the
relaxation of the limits announced yesterday, but the government will still
be pressed about the other areas. These include Hillingdon in London, which
argues that its work with child refugees at Heathrow is not properly
reflected in its grant.
The Local Government Commission, which is to advise on council
restructuring, will begin work on the Isle of Wight on July 1, Mr John
Redwood, the local government minister, told an Association of County
Councils conference yesterday.
He emphasised the need for attention to be paid to the views of local
communities.
</TEXT>
