<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUN 92 / Rise in agreed home loans 'may not be sign of revival'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BARCHARD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BUILDING SOCIETIES pledged Pounds 3.21bn in new mortgage lending last month,
16 per cent up on April. However the Building Societies Association warned
yesterday that the increase in loan agreements did not show that a revival
in the housing market was necessarily on the way.
It said the figure was still below the Pounds 4.07bn in May last year. Net
mortgage lending completed fell from Pounds 1.3bn in April to Pounds 1.24bn
last month.
Building societies provided mortgage loans for 50,000 house purchases last
month compared with 63,000 in May last year.
Last month was also poor for savings, with net receipts at Pounds 179m, down
from Pounds 212m in April. Mr Mark Boleat, director-general of the
association, said societies remained under strong pressure from other forms
of saving.
Because the housing market is so slack, building societies are reducing
their level of borrowing on commercial money markets. Last month they repaid
Pounds 273m of wholesale funding, up from Pounds 223m in April. The
societies have made net payments to the money markets for three of the first
five months of this year.
House prices are likely to fall by 3.5 per cent this year before steady
growth returns to the market over five years, according a study published
yesterday by Charterhouse, the merchant bank.
</TEXT>
