<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUN 92 / Insurers crack down on 'dodgy claims'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE INSURANCE industry yesterday promised a 'blitz' on fraud as it launched
a campaign to combat bogus and inflated claims, which cost it an estimated
Pounds 400m last year.
Mr Mike Jones, chief executive of the Association of British Insurers, which
is co-ordinating the effort, said: 'We aim to identify, spotlight and
prosecute the fraudsters. They must not be allowed to get away with dodgy
claims.'
Fraud by policyholders has added to the problems of the industry, which
announced record trading losses of Pounds 3.3bn last year.
Mr Ian Rushton, chairman of the association, said: 'In the UK, for every
Pounds 1 of premium collected, insurance companies suffered Pounds 1.30 in
claims and expenses.'
The association will tackle fraud with an advertising campaign featuring
case studies of successful prosecutions, which will 'remind the public that
cheating is a crime'.
Cases include 'Arthur', who claimed for a new TV set after pretending that
his old one was damaged, and 'Sally', who added a few things to her
insurance claim after a video was stolen from her house.
'Arthur' was reported by his neighbours after boasting about his plans,
while 'Sally's' plans to cheat came unstuck when the thieves came clean
about the robbery after they were caught.
The campaign, which will cost Pounds 250,000, was launched after a Gallup
poll, commissioned by the association, revealed a widespread public belief
that insurance fraud was extensive.
Of a sample of 1,000 adults interviewed 21 per cent knew of someone who had
put forward a false or inflated claim and 80 per cent thought insurance
fraud was a 'serious or very serious problem'.
Reflecting on the industry's results, Mr Rushton said that the current level
of claims costs was 'unacceptable'. He warned that the 'average family' must
expect to pay Pounds 10 per month more for home and motor insurance this
year.
Motor insurers reported underwriting losses of Pounds 1.2bn. Fire and
accident losses rose to Pounds 3.3bn, compared with Pounds 1.9bn in 1990,
while mortgage indemnity losses amounted to Pounds 1.2bn. The cost of motor
theft claims was up 36 per cent. Subsidence cost Pounds 540m, more than four
times as much as usual.
The one bright spot is continued strong growth in life assurance. Total
premium income increased by 17.8 per cent.
</TEXT>
