FT  24 JUN 92 / Shift in education funding signalled
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE government intends to link some state funding of further education
colleges directly to an expansion of student numbers when it takes over
funding of the sector next year, a CBI conference on education was told
yesterday, Andrew Adonis writes.
Sir John Caines, permanent secretary at the education department, told
delegates that governing councils of the colleges would assume control of
their management - but core funding would come via an quango. He drew a
parallel with polytechnics, whose rapid expansion in the past two years was
stimulated by funding incentives.
The 418 further education colleges and 115 sixth-form colleges in England
and Wales are to be transferred from local authority administration next
spring.
'As independent institutions they (colleges) should be able to respond more
quickly and flexibly than before,' said Sir John. 'Colleges will have a
direct financial incentive to expand participation. Funding will include an
element directly related to student numbers.'
</TEXT>
