<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUN 92 / Anger over County Hall sale
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS and ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR John Major, the prime minister, is set to intervene in the growing
controversy over the future of London's County Hall, amid expressions of
deep resentment by the Japanese purchaser of the site at the government's
continued failure to confirm the sale.
The cabinet is known to be divided on the sale. Several senior ministers -
including Mrs Gillian Shephard, the employment secretary, and Mr John
Patten, education secretary - are believed to support consideration of the
bid by the London School of Economics (LSE) to take over the site.
A clause in the sale contract allows the government to withdraw at any time
until the end of this year. A cabinet committee last week reportedly decided
to allow the LSE to submit a full proposal to move to County Hall, the
former headquarters of the defunct Greater London Council, from its present
site in central London.
Mr Makoto Toyota, London representative of Shirayama, the Japanese property
developer, denied reports that the company had indicated its desire to
withdraw because of the controversy. But he added: 'The present situation is
totally exhausting. We are begging the British government to make clear its
intentions soon if we are to carry on.'
The LSE said last night it was pursuing its bid 'very seriously', and was
'confident' it could match Shirayama's bid for the building - believed to be
in the region of Pounds 60m.
Shirayama plans to turn County Hall into a hotel, retail and sports complex.
The LSE wishes to use it to combine a university campus with a social
science park with office space for applied research units.
The disposal of County Hall is formally the responsibility of the London
Residuary Body, which acts on behalf of the London boroughs. It is legally
obliged to accept the best price for its assets, but the government has the
power to override any deal.
More than 140 MPs have signed a cross-party Commons motion calling on the
government to delay the sale for there to be full consideration of the
suggestion that the LSE should move there. A Commons debate is planned later
this week. Support for the LSE was unanimous in a Lords debate earlier this
month.
</TEXT>
