<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUN 92 / Accounts show 'irregular' payments
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK and NORMA COHEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE 1991 accounts for the Mirror Group show extraordinary losses of Pounds
421.5m from a series of transactions which took place during the few months
up to the collapse of the Maxwell business empire late last year.
The most significant losses and provisions come from deficiencies in the
pension funds and a series of 'irregular transactions'.
Pounds 208.6m for pensions deficiency and related matters. Most comes from
the deficit in the pension funds, estimated at Pounds 192.9m. Deferred tax
of Pounds 62.3m and regular pension costs of Pounds 4m for 1991 reduce the
net provision to Pounds 126.6m.
A second charge of Pounds 10.9m reflects Pounds 16.3m in pension
pre-payments written off because of the misappropriations of assets, net of
Pounds 5.4m in tax.
A third item for Pounds 3.4m - or Pounds 2.3m after tax - is MGN's
commitment to meeting pensions of members of the Maxwell Communication Works
Pension Scheme, who were never employed in the MGN Group, up to June 30
1992.
Pounds 122.4m in losses associated with transactions with Maxwell-controlled
companies including a provision of Pounds 50m against advances from a loan
facility with Bankers Trust.
There is Pounds 48.8m accounted for as interest-bearing deposits with
financial institutions, including Pounds 38.8m with a Maxwell-controlled
company.
A further Pounds 17.1m remains outstanding from a CDollars 35m promissory
note receivable from Robert Maxwell Group, and provisions of Pounds 6.5m
against other balances with Maxwell-controlled companies.
Pounds 50m for extraordinary contingencies. Only two of the contingencies
are quantified: a Dollars 6.5m claim from an individual, believed to be Mr
Mark Booth, formerly the US-based chairman of Maxwell Entertainment Group;
and a claim of Pounds 800,000 from employees of the European newspaper under
contracts they claim were in the name of MGN companies. Pounds 46.4m in
'associated undertakings', including a provision of Pounds 22.2m resulting
from sales of MGN's interest in Donohue; a loss on the disposal of QPI, the
Canadian printing group, of Pounds 17.6m; and a Pounds 6.6m adjustment to
provide additional deferred tax under a change in Canadian tax law.
Pounds 42.6m, split between Pounds 20.5m in fees payable to MGN's advisers
and bankers arising from the default of the group and its restructuring, and
Pounds 22.1m to 'crystallise' potential liability under interest rate
transactions.
Pounds 14.4m in losses arising from a Pounds 200.4m forward foreign currency
contract apparently designed to hedge against servicing a loan in dollars.
This was entered into without consultation with the board.
Pounds 7.3m including a Pounds 4.4m provision against the balance of a loan
outstanding against an employee share ownership trust, Pounds 2.4m from
closure losses and costs of The Racing Times, and Pounds 500,000 in sundry
items.
There was a deferred tax credit of Pounds 70.2m.
</TEXT>
