<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUN 92 / Labour surgeson Israeli tide of discontent
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HUGH CARNEGY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JERUSALEM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
WHEN Israel television announced a few minutes after 10pm last night that
its widely trusted election exit poll was predicting a big victory for the
opposition Labour party, there was an explosion of emotion among party
workers gathered at their headquarters in Tel Aviv.
'We have been waiting for this moment for 15 years,' proclaimed Mr Chaim
Ramon, a senior Labour MP, as party officials cheered, embraced and danced
around him.
Labour has indeed been struggling since 1977 to recapture its position as
the country's premier political force which it occupied, often complacently,
for the first three decades of Israel's existence as a state. Then it was
cast into opposition by the forces of Israel's ideological right wing,
united under the banner of the Likud party and led by the charismatic
Menachem Begin.
Although in 1984 and 1988, Labour managed to claw its way back into
government in coalition with the Likud, it had acquired the stigma of a
force whose time had passed. The Likud, with its commitment to hold on
forever to the occupied territories - the Land of Israel - increasingly saw
itself as the natural party of government.
The tide began to turn early this year when Labour, in a ballot of all its
members, replaced Mr Shimon Peres as leader with Mr Yitzhak Rabin. Where Mr
Peres was widely seen as a cerebral politician over-prone to intrigue and
'soft' towards the Arabs, Mr Rabin had a no-nonsense image that in Israel is
invaluable. He was chief of staff in the triumphant 1967 Six Day War and the
defence minister who in 1988 promised to 'break the bones' of Palestinians
rebelling in the intifada.
Coming from Mr Rabin, the Labour message that it was safe for Israel to
abandon Likud's ideological commitment to the West Bank and Gaza Strip and
make peace on the basis of territorial concessions suddenly sounded more
reasonable.
Labour also benefited from abject Likud incompetence. Under Mr Yitzhak
Shamir's diffident leadership, the Likud had lapsed into vicious and public
intra-party feuding. It also presided over a prolonged period of economic
stagnation the effects of which were sharpened by the flood of immigration
from the former Soviet Union which engulfed the country from 1989.
But Labour under Mr Rabin may yet prove to be a conservative force. He
accepts the need to trade 'land for peace' - the formula demanded by the
Arabs and backed by the US as the basis of a Middle East peace settlement.
But Mr Rabin is against a Palestinian state and opposes giving up large
parts of the West Bank, the Golan Heights and all of East Jerusalem.
Domestically, Labour on paper accepts that the still state-dominated economy
needs a radical dose of reform. But it remains closely allied to the
Histadrut trade union federation which is deeply resistant to many of the
liberalisation programmes, particularly in the labour market, which the vast
majority of economists say Israel must embrace in order to generate the
growth needed to absorb the burden of immigration.
The euphoria sweeping through the party last night was partly an expression
of relief that it had proved wrong the doomsayers who said its time had
passed. But it has much work to do to prove that it is truly the party of
Israel's future.
Of the 3.4m eligible voters, more than 500,000 cast ballots for the first
time.
About 394,000 eligible voters are Israeli Arabs.
The 1.75m West Bank and Gaza Strip Palestinians are ineligible to vote. Most
of the 150,000 Arabs of East Jerusalem who refused Israeli citizenship are
also disqualified.
Voters choose only one of 25 parties contesting the 120 Knesset seats.
Electoral rules say a party must receive 1.5 per cent of the vote to qualify
for a seat in parliament. Those that qualify split the 120 seats based on
the number of votes they receive.
Israeli MPs do not represent any geographical constituency.
