<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUN 92 / Labour party set for victory in Israeli elections: Clear win
for Rabin would provide shot in arm for sluggish peace process
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HUGH CARNEGY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JERUSALEM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ISRAEL'S Labour party was set for a stunning general election victory over
the hardline Likud early today, paving the way for Mr Yitzhak Rabin to take
over as prime minister and implement his promise to accelerate Middle East
peace negotiations.
With 25 per cent of the votes counted, Israeli television projected that
Labour would emerge as the biggest single party by a wide margin, winning 45
of the 120 seats in the Knesset, or parliament. Likud, led by Prime Minister
Yitzhak Shamir, was set to win 32 seats.
The projections, broadly in line with an earlier TV exit poll, signalled the
biggest swing in Israeli politics since Likud came to power in 1977
proclaiming its rightwing ideology. The outcome represented a personal
triumph for Mr Rabin, prime minister in the mid-1970s, and a disaster for Mr
Shamir. Labour supporters took to the streets, cheering and dancing in
celebration.
The main question remaining was which parties Mr Rabin would turn to in an
attempt to form a majority coalition government.
Early projections suggested he would have the option of joining forces with
Meretz, an alliance of leftwing and pro-peace parties, with backing outside
the government from two small Arab parties. Meretz was forecast to win 12
seats and the Arab parties five.
But Mr Rabin signalled that he would prefer a broader-based government,
possibly even including Likud. He said: 'We'll aspire to a coalition which
will express the mainstream of the people . . . we will want to include all
the forces which identify with our way - the advancement of peace while
maintaining security.'
Mr Shamir, 76, is now likely to come under strong pressure to step down as
party leader. But he was defiant, saying: 'Tonight, all over the world and
in the Middle East, people are rejoicing (that the Likud has fallen). I say
to them your happiness is premature, the Likud is not going down. It is
alive and well and will continue its just struggle.'
A victory of the scale forecast would be a resounding endorsement of Mr
Rabin, who took over as Labour leader from Mr Shimon Peres earlier this
year.
The main consequence of a clear Labour victory may be a boost for the peace
process. Mr Shamir had refused to yield any of the occupied territories in
return for peace and appeared lukewarm on conceding the initial stage of
Palestinian autonomy. Mr Rabin and Labour are committed to giving up at
least some of the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip. They are willing to
move quickly to an autonomy agreement.
The forecast of a Labour victory was welcomed by Jordan and the Palestine
Liberation Organisation.
Tide of discontent Page 4
