FT  24 JUN 92 / International Company News: Giat turns in FFr400m deficit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM DAWKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GIAT Industries, the French state-owned armaments maker, yesterday revealed
a 1991 loss of FFr400m (Dollars 75.9m) and said it would have to shed 2,000
of its 17,000 jobs to adjust to reduced defence spending.
The loss compares with a FFr600m deficit in 1990 and is the first time the
formerly secretive Giat has published its results. It was transformed two
years ago from a defence ministry agency into a semi-autonomous state-owned
company.
The defence industry faced 'severe rationalisation' and job losses would
accelerate, said Mr Pierre Chiquet, chairman. He warned that the outlook for
the group this year was more difficult than in 1991, but maintained that
Giat would still hit its target of breaking even in 1993.
The group, which manufactures the Leclerc battle tank, has been attempting
to boost exports to soften the impact of the downturn. The French army is
expected to buy 800 tanks.
Giat's reduced losses were made on turnover up from FFr6.2bn to FFr11.3bn
over the same period. However, the sales increase mostly reflects the
first-time inclusion of FN Herstahl, the Belgian arms maker bought at the
end of 1990, and Manurhin and Luchaire, two French ammunitions groups.
