</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   STOCKHOLM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
REPOLA, Finland's largest industrial group, yesterday reported a loss (after
financial items) of FM118m (Dollars 27.7m) for the first four months of the
year, compared with a FM206m loss in the same period of 1991.
Operating profit rose to FM478m from FM311, with the group's three
industrial groups - pulp and paper, plastic packaging and metal and
engineering products - showing improvement. Operating profit for the United
Paper Mills forestry arm rose to FM421m from FM230m a year earlier, while
the group made a strong recovery in metals and engineering, posting a FM48m
profit against a FM55m loss.
The improvement was due to a number of factors, including cost-cutting, the
elimination of unprofitable operations and the devaluation of the Finnish
markka last November.
Consolidated sales rose by 22 per cent to FM8.46bn from FM6.92bn a year
earlier. The group's equity-to-assets ratio at the end of April was 27.5 per
cent, against 28 per cent.
