<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUN 92 / International Company News: Renault, Volvo ventures
strengthen cars alliance
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM DAWKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
RENAULT, the French state-owned carmaker, and Volvo, its Swedish partner,
are to strengthen their alliance by pooling most of their car component
purchasing and all their quality control activities.
The companies have agreed to set up two joint ventures in component-buying
and quality control to 'put together the respective resources of Renault and
Volvo Car Corporation so as to act as if the two groups were one company,'
the French company said.
This is one of the biggest steps in the Renault-Volvo alliance since the
pair agreed to take cross-shareholdings in each others' parents and
subsidiaries two years ago. But it was not a prelude to a full merger of the
groups' car and truckmaking businesses, added Renault. Shortly before
retiring last month, Mr Raymond Levy, the former chairman, said a merger was
possible, but such a course was not the only way to increase co-operation
with Volvo.
The components move will boost the economies of scale already achieved by
helping the partners to secure bigger discounts from suppliers. They now
jointly buy 15 per cent of their components from common makers through a
committee set up in October 1990. The companies hoped to lift that figure to
80 per cent very shortly, said Renault.
Renault spends FFr50bn (Dollars 9.46bn) a year on buying components,
representing 60 per cent of its manufacturing costs. Volvo's components bill
stands at FFr14bn. If the two reached their 80 per cent target, they would
pool FFr51.2bn of annual spending.
Before yesterday's announcement, Volvo estimated that in two to five years
it would save SKr800m (Dollars 141.6m) annually from joint component buying
alone. Renault has not put a figure to its savings in this area, but
estimates it has saved FFr1bn on development costs by using some Volvo
engines.
The joint venture on quality control aims to ensure the partners use common
methods and standards. It applies to the manufacturing process as well as to
finished cars. Along with the components venture, it builds on existing
co-operation - a joint quality management board set up last September.
Both operations will be based in Paris under management to be chosen on
merit from either partner. They will be set up as European economic interest
groupings, a streamlined structure set up under EC law to encourage
cross-frontier alliances.
Neither of the joint activities would apply to the partners' truckmaking
divisions, which have fewer suppliers in common, said Renault.
To date, the partners have created a joint research centre in France;
partially merged their sales divisions for French cars and light commercial
vehicles; and co-operated in the production of two buses.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
