<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUN 92 / UK Company News: Whitecroft falls 27% and restructuring
continues
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN HAMILTON FAZEY, Northern Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WHITECROFT, the Cheshire-based group which last week announced a severe
dividend curtailment to dampen expectations ahead of its results, yesterday
reported a 27 per cent drop in pre-tax profits to Pounds 4.49m for the year
to end-March.
The figure for the previous year amounted to Pounds 6.11m before taking into
account an exceptional provision of Pounds 3.3m.
Whitecroft is undergoing a reconstruction to get through the recession. It
is still disengaging from property but has largely completed reorganisation
of its lighting, building products, medical cotton fibre and textiles
businesses, with cost savings now likely.
The final dividend curtailment to 0.7p making a 4p (10p) total, resulted
from an extraordinary item, an extra Pounds 8m gross provision for
withdrawal from property development. The figure worked out at Pounds 6.43m
net and was on top of a Pounds 5m net provision made last year.
The commercial property portfolio has now been revalued at Pounds 20m.
Whitecroft sold its housebuilding division in January, reducing borrowings
by Pounds 6m. The ongoing sales of houses retained are expected to bring in
Pounds 4m, with another Pounds 800,000 of deferred consideration to come.
Mr Peter Goold, chairman, said all construction was completed and several
lettings had now been achieved.
The biggest single development was a complex of shops and offices in
Sheffield. Smaller ones were mainly scattered in the Thames Valley. Likely
prices would be balanced against financing costs to optimise future
disposals.
On the pre-tax line the pre-tax comparison of Pounds 6.11m has been restated
as Pounds 2.81m following the Accounting Standards Board's new consensus on
restructuring costs. This required Whitecroft to charge restructuring of its
textiles division to the 1990-91 current account, although one gain was to
reduce last year's tax bill by Pounds 1m.
Turnover fell 10 per cent to Pounds 129.19m and operating profits 48 per
cent to Pounds 4.6m. However, sustained investment in computer aided design
and flexible manufacturing systems enabled the lighting division to make a
profit of Pounds 4.52m (Pounds 6.68m) in spite of recession.
It used technology to process larger numbers of smaller orders efficiently
as big orders for office blocks withered. The niche market, medical cotton
fibres business, fell slightly to Pounds 1.79m, while textiles - a dyeing,
finishing and coatings business - held at Pounds 700,000.
Building products lost Pounds 1.02m after breaking even last year. Demand
fell for textured wallcoatings, but Mr Goold was expecting good progress
from high performance, fire-resistant doors as safety regulations push up
standards in offices and public buildings.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 24
</PAGE>
