FT  24 JUN 92 / Parliament and Politics: Support grows for private landlords
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN, Public Policy Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THERE IS widespread support among politicians and housing experts for
reviving the private landlord system, a report commissioned by the Joseph
Rowntree Foundation, the social research organisation, said yesterday.
The report called for incentives to encourage private landlords and to
secure funding for rented housing from financial institutions. It also said
there should be improved tax breaks and measures to make it easier to regain
possession of properties let out.
Among those who have given 'broad agreement' to such measures is Ms Sheila
McKechnie, director of the housing charity Shelter, and businesses that
provide private rented accommodation.
The report said reversing the decline in private rented housing was the only
way to meet the demand that councils and housing associations could not
meet. Revival of the sector would require government subsidies to bridge the
gap between the landlord's likely income from rents and the returns
available from comparable investments, the report added.
Income tax exemptions on rent and capital gains tax allowances such as those
offered to owner-occupiers should also be considered.
The report advocated steps to reassure landlords that they could regain
possession of their properties with reasonable speed from tenants who did
not pay rent. It said court procedures should be streamlined to eliminate
delays - now as long as six months - in obtaining a hearing.
Sir George Young, housing minister, welcomed the report. 'I hope we shall
succeed in creating a sector in which the major financial institutions - the
pension funds and insurance companies - feel they can invest with confidence
once more,' he said.
The Future of Private Renting, Joseph Rowntree Foundation, 40 Water End,
York YO3 6LP. Pounds 7.50.
</TEXT>
