FT  24 JUN 92 / Tight security as thousands flock to the City
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THERE will be tight security at today's Lloyd's of London annual general
meeting, the biggest event at the insurance market since an IRA bomb shook
damaged neighbouring buildings in April. The bomb caused only slight damage
at Lloyd's itself, but in its aftermath entry to the market's steel and
glass headquarters has understandably become more time-consuming.
Lloyd's claims that there should be room for any Name to attend the meeting
as long as members bring with them appropriate membership and security
passes. Seats, restricted to the ground floor and to the edges of the
galleries of floors one, two and three will be at a premium although there
is adequate standing room and TV monitors will relay proceedings to watchers
from upper floors.
In any event Names are advised to arrive early - at the building's main
concourse reception in Lime Street for the meeting which begins at 10.30am.
As for the procedings themselves, Mr David Coleridge, backed by members of
the Lloyd's Council and leading executives at the corporation, will speak on
the market's losses - a record Pounds 2bn in its most recent underwriting
year 1989 - and prospects for Lloyd's.
Formal business is limited to a presentation of the annual report and
accounts of the Lloyd's Corporation and a vote of thanks. Little will be
decided - the meeting's formal business is limited but Names are free to ask
questions.
