<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUN 92 / London expected to lag EC city league
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN, Economics Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GREATER LONDON will see the slowest economic growth of the European
Community's main city areas for the first half of the 1990s, while Greater
Manchester will be second from the bottom of the EC league, a report from a
group of research bodies says.
The European Economic Research Consortium forecasts in a report on prospects
for EC and Austrian city regions that five of the 10 slowest-growing areas
will be in the UK.
It expects the fastest-growing UK city region to be Edinburgh, ranked 23 out
of 32, followed by Cardiff and Birmingham at 24 and 25 respectively, while
the Glasgow-Strathclyde area is forecast to be 27th.
These areas are expected to achieve annual increases of at least 2 per cent
in gross value added between 1989 and 1996, while the value added to goods
and services produced in London is expected to grow by only 1 per cent a
year in that period. For Manchester, the consortium forecasts annual
value-added growth of 1.4 per cent.
Madrid and Berlin are expected to be the fastest-growing EC cities with
annual value-added growth of 4.7 and 4.5 per cent respectively.
The UK cities' poor growth outlook reflects the deep UK recession. But
London has special problems including traffic congestion, high costs and
de-industrialisation, while Manchester will be affected by a further decline
in its textile and defence-related industries.
European Regional Prospects. Cambridge Econometrics, 21 St Andrew's Street,
Cambridge CB2 3AX. Pounds 1,400, or Pounds 70 for an abridged version.
</TEXT>
