FT  24 JUN 92 / Channel 5 contender pulls out
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GARY MEAD, Marketing Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
EDINBURGH-based Channel S Television yesterday abandoned plans to bid to
operate the Channel 5 terrestrial television network, two weeks before the
bid deadline, blaming uncertainty about costs.
The contractor for Channel 5 will have to pay for the retuning of about 3m
video recorders to prevent interference from the new channel. The costs of
retuning video recorders accounts for about Pounds 50m of the Pounds 200m
estimated overall cost of launching the channel.
Mr Justin Dukes, former managing director of Channel 4 and in charge of the
Channel S plans to bid for Channel 5, said that the retuning costs 'cannot
be precisely predicted'.
He added that cost estimates 'have taken the business from being possible
to, in our opinion, an impossible one'.
The two remaining serious contenders are the Entertainment Channel - a
consortium of Time Warner, TV-am and the Daily Telegraph group - and the
Five TV group, which includes Thames TV, Sony Pictures International and
Canwest Global Communications, a Canadian-based international broadcaster.
