<HEADLINE>
FT  23 JUN 92 / World Stock Markets (America): Sluggishness of US recovery
spreads gloom
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
ALTHOUGH US share prices recovered from heavy early losses yesterday, market
sentiment remained depressed amid deepening gloom about the sluggishness of
the US economic recovery and its effect on corporate earnings, writes
Patrick Harverson in New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average was finally off 4.55 at 3,280.80, a
substantial rally from early afternoon when it had been 30 points down.
The Standard &amp; Poor's 500 lost a net 0.27 at 403.40, he American SE
composite shed 3.77 to 375.62 and the Nasdaq composite gave up 4.47 at
549.73. Turnover on the New York SE was 169m shares.
The market has fallen in four out of the last five trading days (the only
exception being Friday when options-related buying lifted the Dow 11
points), and analysts have interpreted the declines as part of a concerted
sell-off by investors - a substantial correction of the recent bull phase.
Some say that an increasing number of investors now believe equities are
overvalued and, troubled by the feebleness of the economic recovery, find
more reasons to sell stocks than to buy them.
Merck bucked the trend, rising Dollars 2 1/4 to Dollars 50 1/2 in heavy
trading on news that the US Food and Drug Administration (FDA) had approved
the company's Proscar drug, used in the treatment of enlarged prostate
glands.
Another rare gain was recorded by Time Warner, which rose Dollars  3/4 to
Dollars 110 7/8 as investors celebrated news that the new Batman Returns
film, produced by subsidiary Warner Brothers, earned more than Dollars 46m
in gross receipts over its opening weekend.
Boeing eased Dollars  3/8 to Dollars 41 7/8 on reports that the aircraft
manufacturer is fighting European consortium Airbus Industries for a Dollars
2.4bn contract for jetliners from United Airlines.
International Rectifier dropped Dollars 2 1/4 to Dollars 8 1/8 after the
company warned that previous earnings projections were too optimistic and
said its fiscal fourth-quarter net would be only slightly in the black.
The losses on Latin American, and especially Mexican, markets took their
toll of certain stocks, notably Telmex, down Dollars 2 7/8 at Dollars 44 7/8
, Mexico Fund, Dollars 1 5/8 lower at Dollars 20 7/8 , and Brazil Fund, off
Dollars 1 3/8 at Dollars 17 1/2 .
On the Nasdaq market, Heart Technology plunged a further Dollars 2 1/8 to
Dollars 9 1/4 after voluntarily recalling its coronary rotablator device
following five reported failures. On Friday the stock fell sharply when the
company asked customers to stop using the product.
Canada
TORONTO rallied from early weakness in line with Wall Street, the TSE 300
index ending a net 10.2 off at 3,340.7 after a near 30-point initial fall.
Declines led rises by 342 to 219 and volume was 23m shares.
The gold group recovered from Friday's decline, rising 1.37 per cent. The
New York spot gold price was up USDollars 2.75 to USDollars 343.25 an ounce.
</TEXT>
