<HEADLINE>
FT  23 JUN 92 / International Capital Markets: Argentine privatisation by
stealth - The flotation of YPF, the national oil group
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN BARHAM
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE privatisation of Yacimientos Petroliferos Fiscales (YPF), Argentina's
national oil company, gets underway early next year. Bit by bit, the group
will be floated on local and international equity markets with the aim of
eliminating the federal government's shareholding.
A start will be made in January with the sale of American Depositary
Receipts (ADRs) in New York and London, together with straight equity in
Buenos Aires.
Eventually these tranches, amounting to 51 per cent of YPF, are expected to
raise around Dollars 4bn.
Rather than place the shares on the market at one go, the government plans
to ration the flotation over a number of tranches. The rest of YPF will be
held by employees with 10 per cent and provincial governments with 39 per
cent.
However, the government has yet to get parliamentary approval for the sale.
The government submitted a bill in November, expecting it to sail through
Congress. But senators want the state to retain a minority stake in YPF.
Mr Jose Estenssoro, the YPF president who spent most of his career in the
private-sector oil industry, says his ultimate aim is to slim down YPF into
an integrated, well-balanced oil company with annual assets of Dollars 8bn.
His reform plan was drawn up together with McKinsey and Arthur D. Little,
the US management consultants. This calls for drastic reshaping of YPF. He
says: 'I am downsizing the company by cutting away all the fat.'
Eventually the workforce will be reduced to 12,000 from 52,000 in 1990.
The group has already raised Dollars 1.53bn from asset sales, mainly the
disposal of stakes in oilfields. Other assets earmarked for sale include
pipeline networks and a tanker fleet.
YPF's financial performance is beginning to improve. It estimates 1991 sales
at Dollars 5bn, which would be an increase of around 20 per cent on 1990,
and says profits for last year should emerge at more than Dollars 300m.
In the four months to April, YPF's share of national oil output fell to 59
per cent, or 5.93m cubic metres. Two years ago, it produced 97 per cent of
Argentina's oil.
Mr Estenssoro says new management and control systems should be implemented
and operational by January, 1993 and restructuring should be at least 70 to
80 per cent complete by 1993.
This, he says, should leave the ground well preparted for the first
international issue of shares in YPF.
</TEXT>
