<HEADLINE>
FT  23 JUN 92 / International Company News: France sets Total share price
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By AGENCIES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE French government has set a price of FFr230 per share on the 12.4 per
cent stake in oil company Total that it is selling to the public, the
Finance Ministry said in a statement, agencies report from Paris.
The ministry also said French stock market authorities had approved its plan
to exchange another 6.5 per cent of Total stock for Total investment
certificates held by investors.
The government will raise FFr5.27bn (Dollars 1bn) from the sale of its 22.9m
shares in Total and its direct shareholding in Total will be reduced to 15
per cent from 34 per cent. The share sale will open today and close on June
25. The certificate swap will open shortly.
French investors will be offered 8m shares under the sale. There will also
be an international offering of 7.5m shares plus a US tranche of 7.4m
shares. Depending on demand, the French tranche could be increased by 10 per
cent with shares taken from the international offering.
When it disclosed its intention to trim its stake in Total, the government
indicated it would retain a 5 per cent direct shareholding in Total, but did
not make clear how the remaining 10 per cent stake would be distributed. The
ministry said state-owned bank Credit Lyonnais and Assurances Generales de
France, a state-controlled insurance group, would each take 4 per cent of
the 10 per cent stake. The remaining 2 per cent stake would go to Groupement
des Assurances Nationales, a state-sector insurance group.
</TEXT>
