<HEADLINE>
FT  23 JUN 92 / Parliament and Politics: Government 'firm' on EC hours limit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART and PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE UK government might accept a compromise on the European Community
working time directive but is not prepared to agree to the controversial
48-hour limit on the working week, even if it is delayed for 10 years.
A meeting of senior cabinet ministers yesterday finalised Britain's 'bottom
line' on the directive, which will almost certainly be voted on at the
meeting of EC ministers responsible for employment legislation in Luxembourg
tomorrow.
Britain is insisting that there should be full flexibility on designating
Sunday as an official day of rest; that negotiations on directives between
employers and employees can take place at local and not just national level;
and that employees should be free to work more than 48 hours a week if it
does not put their health at risk.
The first two points are unlikely to cause difficulty, but several countries
would prefer to keep the 48-hour limit, even if it is delayed for 10 years
as proposed by the Portuguese. If Britain cannot win an indefinite
postponement of the 48-hour limit it will probably launch a legal challenge
against the directive.
Although Britain alone cannot vote down the directive, ministers believe
that other EC countries are less likely to impose the directive on the UK
after the Danish referendum result.
One senior minister said after yesterday's talks that the government had
agreed a position that combined 'firmness with reason'. It was anxious to
avoid an open breach with its EC partners on the eve of the Lisbon summit,
but there were limits beyond which its supporters in the Commons would not
accept compromise.
Mrs Gillian Shephard, the employment secretary, today meets her opposite
number in Paris, Mrs Martine Aubry, for what might be a crucial last-minute
negotiation on the directive.
The French have been among the most enthusiastic supporters of the
directive, including the 48-hour limit, but Mrs Aubry has a reputation for
pragmatism.
</TEXT>
