<HEADLINE>
FT  23 JUN 92 / Parliament and Politics: Debate may foil Tory Euro-sceptics
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN MAJOR may directly confront his critics in the Conservative party by
holding a full-scale Commons debate on Britain's priorities for its
presidency of the European Community.
Senior ministers said the prime minister was considering a debate before
parliament begins its summer recess next month.
The suggestion came amid indications that European enthusiasts in the
cabinet have decided to move on to the offensive against the Euro-sceptics
in the Tory party who are opposing the Maastricht accords on European Union.
Mr Major, who will tonight hold talks in Downing Street with Mr Jacques
Delors on his plans for the presidency, has made clear that the legislation
to ratify Maastricht will not return to the Commons until the late autumn.
But ministers said that he might seek to isolate the Euro-sceptics by
calling a more general debate before the recess.
The debate would be framed so as to prevent either Labour or rebels in his
own party from forcing a substantial vote while rallying support for the
government's position.
Mr Major has put enlargement of the Community, the completion of the single
market and tight controls on spending at the centre of his agenda for the
next six months.
In a speech last night Mr David Hunt, the Welsh secretary, fired the first
shots in what colleagues said would be a determined campaign by the
ministerial enthusiasts for European integration.
Mr Hunt, whose speech was approved in advance by Downing Street, called on
Conservatives to embrace a 'bold vision' of Europe, seizing the opportunity
to create an ever more united community of peoples while preserving national
diversities.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 11
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT922-1307</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CFWA9AE6FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920623
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  23 JUN 92 / Parliament and Politics: Labour tries to heal its European
wound / Examining the party's division over Maastricht
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR Gerald Kaufman is enjoying a characteristically combative swansong as
Labour's outgoing shadow foreign secretary.
Last weekend, he again challenged the government to come to the Commons and
spell out its plans for the future of the bill ratifying the Maastricht
treaty.
Speaking in his Manchester, Gorton, constituency, he warned that Ireland's
firm 'yes' in its referendum last week would do nothing to solve the
quandary on how to proceed without splitting the Conservative party.
'Unless and until a clear way through is shown for the treaty, it will be
improper for the government to ask parliament to pass the Maastricht Bill,'
Mr Kaufman said, comfortable in the certainty that no such 'way through' is
likely before his return to the back benches.
If his invitation to debate is declined, it is not impossible that Labour
will use some of its own time allocation to table a suitably caustic
European motion of its own.
But the wording will have to be delicately chosen. There is now plenty of
evidence that the Danish referendum result has left Labour quite as divided
over the future of the Maastricht accords as the government.
In the past 10 days alone, Mr Neil Kinnock, the outgoing leader, has had to
decline the presidency of the Confederation of Socialist parties and hint
that Labour just might support a national referendum on Maastricht.
Both moves are indicators of the deep ferment on the Labour benches as the
old leadership ebbs away. 'Gerald is demob happy, Neil is buckling under the
pressure and John Smith can't say anything as he's not yet elected,' one
worried party disciplinarian commented yesterday.
That mood is beginning to alarm longstanding Labour 'Europeans' who fear
that the party is now risks sacrificing its hard-fought struggle for
credibility on the Continent for a short-term tactical victory in
Westminster.
Mr Giles Radice, the Euro-phile MP for Durham North, appears to have had a
premonition of such a danger. His new book, Offshore: Britain and the
European Idea, published next week, warns against Labour being a 'reluctant
European' party or even reverting to an anti-European stance.
Yet there are probably no more than 25 anti-Europeans in the parliamentary
Labour party. The real threat now comes from a pro-European faction, driven
by the newly reformed Tribune group led by two prominent soft-left
backbenchers, Mr Peter Hain and Ms Clare Short.
They are arguing that the Danish referendum outcome offers an opportunity to
re-open the treaty negotiations to address Labour's demands for, for
example, more democratic accountability of Community institutions and
British adhesion to the social chapter.
Such arguments provoke despair among longstanding Labour Europhiles who say
that any short-term gain from defeating the government on ratification would
be paid in lost credibility abroad.
As Mr Radice points out, if France approves Maastricht in its own
plebiscite, Labour opposition to the treaty - on whatever grounds - could
end up scuppering the social chapter it publicly espouses.
The Tribunites counter that factors such as the highly-monetarist
convergence criteria for economic union are so flawed as to justify
rejection of the Maastricht terms.
'If Britain voting it (Maastricht ) down led to a renegotiation, I might go
for it,' Ms Short said.
In part, this owes much to a growing appetite for confrontation - both with
the government and, arguably, the party leadership - provoked by the
frustrations of opposition. Yet fellow socialists in Brussels - Labour MEPs
included - say it demonstrates an historic unreliability and general lack of
seriousness over the European project.
For Mr John Smith, a month away from his coronation as leader, the European
question will be his first test.
So far, as an impeccable European, he has delicately endorsed the
Tribunites' criticisms of Maastricht as 'not enough,' but stressed the need
to work closely with Labour's European allies.
Opposed to using a referendum as sticking plaster over party divisions, his
instincts will be to back another neutral abstention when the treaty comes
to a vote.
Yet with Labour in its current mood there is a danger that, just months
after taking office, he may face one of the party's biggest rebellions since
the bad old days of the early 1980s.
</TEXT>
