FT  23 JUN 92 / Parliament and Politics: Boundary proposals attacked
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE NUMBER of people eligible to vote in England and Wales might be as much
as 1.7m higher than the number registered, Mr Alistair Darling, shadow home
affairs spokesman, asserted yesterday.
He was moving a Labour amendment to the government bill which seeks to
ensure that changes in the boundaries of constituencies are implemented
before the next general election.
Labour's amendment would allow boundary commissions to delay submitting
their reports to the government if they were satisfied that the register on
which they were basing them was inaccurate.
While it was known electoral registers were inaccurate in many areas,
boundary commissions were nevertheless expected to report on the basis of
the information they contained, Mr Darling said.
He laid much of the blame for the unsatisfactory situation on the poll tax,
which had made 'breaking the law an acceptable act to many people who would
never ever have contemplated it in the past'.
Mr Kenneth Clarke, home secretary, insisted that British rates of voter
registration were high by international standards.
The Labour amendment fell by 59 votes (303-244).
Individuals earning more than Pounds 50,000 a year will be Pounds 21,000
better off this financial year than if 1978-79 income tax rates had simply
been indexed, the Treasury said in a parliamentary written answer last
night. Those earning less than Pounds 5,000 will be just Pounds 150 better
off.
