<HEADLINE>
FT  23 JUN 92 / Job adverts by phone to be probed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHIYO NAKAMOTO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE USE of premium-rate telephone services to advertise jobs and business
opportunities is to be investigated by the industry's watchdog body after a
sharp increase in complaints last year.
The review was ordered by the Independent Committee for the Supervision of
Standards of Telephone Information Services (Icstis) after it received
allegations that some of the business and job opportunities advertised did
not exist or were advertised in a misleading manner.
Complainants said they had made telephone calls at 48p a minute - 36p cheap
rate - in response to advertisements offering job opportunities, to find
that none existed.
The overall number of complaints about all premium-rate telephone services
rose 45 per cent to 6,753 from 4,658 in 1990. A record number of services
were removed last year.
Sir Louis Blom-Cooper QC, chairman of Icstis, said complaints about
employment services increased more than fivefold to 843, about 13 per cent
of total complaints.
In one case a service advertised in Scotland claiming to be looking for
people to pack goods at home for distribution was found by Icstis to have no
goods and no vacancies.
Sir Louis said callers to some such services were sometimes faced with a
charge for applying for the vacancy or opportunity, as well as the premium
cost of the call.
The employment services were only the most recent and conspicuous among a
number of services that have fallen foul of guidelines for use of the
premium-rate telephone services drawn up by Icstis.
As the industry has grown from Pounds 67m in 1987 to Pounds 200m last year,
according to industry estimates, the number of services removed or amended
trebled last year to 665 and 370 respectively. Icstis ordered the withdrawal
of 833 advertisements that did not comply with its guidelines. Sir Louis
said persistent offenders tended to be in the adult entertainment sector.
Icstis has strengthened its rules on misleading services and advertisements
and has included in its revised code of practice a requirement that
interactive services lasting more than 10 minutes should inform callers of
the total cost of the call and give regular warnings of additional time
spent connected.
In addition to complaints about employment services, those relating to
competitions offering prizes to callers approximately doubled while those
relating to sales promotions - mailings inviting people to call premium
numbers offering incentives - rose tenfold.
</TEXT>
