<HEADLINE>
FT  23 JUN 92 / More at school after 16
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LAST YEAR saw a big rise in the number of 16-year-olds staying on at school
in England and Wales, according to a report by the Careers Service published
yesterday.
The report shows that of the half million pupils who reached school leaving
age last summer, 61 per cent - the highest proportion ever - remained in
full-time education. In 1990 it was 53 per cent, and in 1989 48 per cent.
If Youth Training is included, 76 per cent of those eligible to leave school
remained in full-time education or training last year compared with 70 per
cent in 1989.
For the first time in recent decades, that puts England and Wales within
reach of France and Germany where the full-time staying-on rate is between
80 per cent and 90 per cent - although many people doubt the comparability
of Youth Training, which accounted for 15 per cent of last year's school
leavers, with Continental training schemes.
The recession is clearly a factor in the increase.
The Careers Service report, published by the Association of County Councils,
shows a far higher staying-on rate among girls (68 per cent) than among boys
(55 per cent).
Among girls leaving school to go into jobs, traditional feminine career
patterns persist unchecked. Most girls went into clerical, retail,
hairdressing and the 'caring' professions. The five most popular occupations
for boys were construction, retail, mechanical and production engineering,
processing and the armed forces and police.
The survey shows large regional variations. With 68 per cent of 16-year-olds
remaining in full-time education, the south-east tops the league. Behind it
come outer London, (67 per cent), the south-west (66 per cent) and inner
London (63 per cent). The north scores lowest, with only 51 per cent staying
on.
School Leavers' Destinations. Association of County Councils, 66a Eaton Sq,
London SW1W 9BH. Pounds 10.
</TEXT>
