<PROFILE>_AN-CFWA9AERFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920623
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  23 JUN 92 / Imports continue strong rise but exports up 4%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN, Economics Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE sharp declines last month in Britain's visible trade and provisional
current-account deficits represent more a return to normality than any
significant improvement in the nation's trade performance.
While exports rose 4 per cent in May to an all-time high of Pounds 9.17bn
and last month's seasonally adjusted visible trade deficit, at Pounds 845m,
was the lowest monthly total so far this year, imports have continued to
advance strongly.
Moreover, at Pounds 1.19bn, the latest monthly visible trade deficit less
oil and the so-called erratic items such as aircraft, ships, North Sea
installations and precious stones, was consistent with that measure of the
deficit for most months since the middle of last year. The Central
Statistical Office and the Treasury consider that the measure gives a
reasonable guide to underlying trade performance.
The good news in the latest trade figures is that export growth is broadly
based. Taking the figures for volume exports, Britain exported more of every
type of product except certain consumer goods in the three months to the end
of May compared with the three months to the end of February. Altogether,
volume exports rose by 2.5 per cent between the two periods and were up 5
per cent in the three months to the end of May compared with the comparable
three months last year.
The bad news is that imports grew more strongly, with growth in volume terms
of 4 per cent in the latest three months compared with the three months to
the end of February and an increase of 7.5 per cent compared with the three
months to end-May last year. Those figures give a better guide to the trend
of Britain's imports than the 1.5 per cent drop in the value of imports to
Pounds 10bn last month from April's Pounds 10.18bn.
Excluding erratic items, the latest trade returns show that volume exports
of manufactured goods rose by 2.5 per cent in the latest three months
compared with the previous three months.
Volume imports of manufactured goods, including finished manufactures,
increased by 4.5 per cent in the same period. A notable feature was an 18
per cent jump in the volume imports of cars in the latest three months while
car exports in volume terms increased by only 1 per cent compared with the
three months to the end of February.
It is too early to judge whether the latest figures point to a serious
reversal of the recent revival of UK car exports.
