<HEADLINE>
FT  23 JUN 92 / Companies restrict business travel
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DANIEL GREEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
COMPANIES ARE encour-aging employees to travel by road and rail rather than
air in response to the recession, according to a report published yesterday.
The amount spent on rail travel rose by two thirds to Pounds 2bn last year
compared with 1989. Spending on air travel fell 21 per cent to Pounds 4.5bn
over the same period, according to the report by American Express on travel
and entertainment.
The fall in spending on air travel did not necessarily reflect a fall in
passenger numbers. 'People are also being encouraged to change to
lower-class seats,' said Mr Jim Jamison, vice-president of travel management
services at American Express.
The report also noted a fall of 14 per cent in spending on hotels. That was
partly made up for by a rise in spending on fuel.
The total amount spent on travel and entertainment fell from about Pounds
20bn in 1989 to more than Pounds 18bn last year. Some 37 per cent was
incurred on overseas trips.
The fall was partly a result of declining employment, said Mr Donald
Osborne, the report's author. Those companies which have survived over the
past two years saw spending rise 4 per cent. Retail prices rose 14.2 per
cent over the same period.
Business travel and entertainment accounted for 6.6 per cent of total
business costs last year, and amounted to about Pounds 1,000 per employee.
Four out of five businesses expected spending to increase parallel or faster
than - revenues.
The report also said the number of women business travellers had risen to 17
per cent of the total last year from 11 per cent in 1989. Many hotels were
now concentrating on providing more convenient facilities for women
travellers as numbers increased.
In spite of the sums spent, almost half the 407 companies questioned did not
have a written travel policy. A total of 44 per cent of companies said they
had no arrangements for securing corporate discounts.
Three quarters of companies had recently taken steps to control spending on
travel and entertainment. But almost a third said they were not yet
satisfied with their efforts to control this spending.
Business Travel &amp; Expense Management Report 1992. American Express Europe,
Portland House, Stag Place, London SW1E 5BZ. Pounds 50.
</TEXT>
