FT  23 JUN 92 / York chop
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Shambles, built in the 13th century as the city's butchery centre, is
set to lose its last butcher's shop, Chris Tighe writes.
Dewhurst has earmarked its branch in the street for closure as part of a
national programme to cut its outlets from 1,000 to 400. One of the
best-preserved medieval streets in Europe, the Shambles was formerly called
the Fleshammels, meaning meat counters.
It has 47 shops, most of which were once butcher's. Dewhurst said: 'The
Shambles really is a tourist haunt now. It's not the ideal trading
environment for a butcher's' An increase in supermarkets in and around York
has also curbed trade.
</TEXT>
