FT  23 JUN 92 / Pressure over Maxwell report grows
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH and NORMA COHEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CALLS FOR the government to publish the report by Imro, the investment
management regulatory organisation, into the supervision of the Maxwell
companies intensified yesterday.
MPs campaigning on behalf of the Maxwell pensioners believe that the way the
government is allowing the row over publishing the report to continue while
extracts are selectively leaked jeopardises the work of the special unit set
up to recover pension-fund assets.
Mr Frank Field, Labour MP for Birkenhead and one of the MPs leading the
campaign on behalf of the pensioners, has warned the government that it
risks accusations of a 'cover-up' if it continues to allow attention to
focus on what might still remain secret in the report, rather than on the
role of the banks and others.
Pressure has been heightened by a report in the London Evening Standard that
the Imro report says the Bank of England prevented Robert Maxwell purchasing
two British merchant banks in the late 1980s.
The Bank of England declined to comment on the report, saying it could not
discuss its supervisory activities.
The newspaper report said the Bank told Imro Maxwell wanted to purchase
Guiness Peat in 1987 and in 1989 sought to take control of the private
merchant banking group Robert Fraser.
The Bank confirmed its policy would be to require any purchaser of a 15 per
cent stake in a UK bank to pass a 'fit and proper' assessment and Maxwell
never acquired a stake larger than that in any UK bank.
The Financial Times last week received a telephone call from a woman
claiming to have a copy of the report and offering it for sale. Sources in
the Evening Standard said the paper had not bought the Imro report, although
it had heard that an individual had been offering to sell it.
Last night the Securities and Investments Board and Imro were considering a
formal investigation into allegations that the document had been offered for
sale. Only limited numbers were printed and each was numbered.
Mr Michael Meacher, shadow social security secretary, yesterday demanded a
government statement in the Commons about publishing the Imro report.
Rescue for MGN, Page 21
