<DATE>920623
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  23 JUN 92 / Clinton refines economic policy: Strategy seeks to create
jobs through Dollars 50bn-a-year investment
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
GOVERNOR Bill Clinton, the presumptive Democratic presidential candidate,
yesterday returned his campaign to policy specifics, in which he excels,
with a detailed reformulation of his economic programme.
Refining the policies he endorsed during the four-month Democratic primary
campaign, Mr Clinton called for an economic strategy that would create jobs
by investing Dollars 50bn (Pounds 27bn) a year in education and
infrastructure, while cutting the federal budget deficit by half over four
years.
Mr Clinton, the Arkansas governor, launched his programme at a meeting of
the US Conference of Mayors in Houston. He emphasised proposals for 'Dollars
20bn a year of hard, federal dollars' to invest in transport and information
technology infrastructure, as well as the creation of urban enterprise zones
 -a policy pressed by Mr Jack Kemp, secretary of housing and urban
development in the Bush administration - and more community policing.
His programme also calls for 'lifetime learning' with investment in
education all the way from kindergarten to adult retraining, as well as
healthcare reforms embracing the 'play or pay' approach, by which employers
would either have to provide health insurance for their employees or pay a
levy into a state-run health insurance fund.
Mr Clinton still supports shifting the tax burden away from middle-income
families towards the wealthiest taxpayers, but he has weakened his proposal
for a middle-class tax cut, which drew from his principal Democratic
opponent, Mr Paul Tsongas, the charge of pandering for votes.
The Clinton programme would now allow middle-income families either a
children's tax credit or a reduction in their income tax rate - but not
both, as he had previously advocated.
Higher income tax rates for the richest 2 per cent of the population,
coupled with a surtax on millionaires, would raise Dollars 17.8bn of
additional revenue in 1993, the Clinton plan says, rising to Dollars 23bn in
1996.
'I believe that during the 1980s the rich got richer and the middle class
took it on the chin,' Mr Clinton said.
The other main sources of revenue in Mr Clinton's programme are additional
cuts in defence spending totalling Dollars 37.5bn over four years, and
measures to tax foreign subsidiaries operating in the US more heavily by
clamping down on their transfer pricing arrangements with their parent
companies.
Mr Clinton estimates that this could raise an additional Dollars 45bn over
four years.
This measure, along with a plan to discourage companies from moving
manufacturing operations to other countries by no longer allowing them to
defer paying tax on overseas earnings, echoes a package put forward in
Congress by Mr Dan Rostenkowski, chairman of the House of Representatives
ways and means committee.
Shying away from the politically sensitive issue of tackling entitlement
programmes such as social security and Medicare, which are the fastest
growing component of the federal budget, Mr Clinton expects only Dollars
4.4bn of savings from entitlement reforms.
Mr Clinton projects a federal budget deficit still totalling Dollars 141bn
in 1996 if growth remains moderate, compared with an expected deficit of
Dollars 400bn this year - a more modest claim than that of Mr Ross Perot,
the prospective independent candidate, who said he could eliminate the
deficit 'without breaking a sweat'.
</TEXT>
