<HEADLINE>
FT  23 JUN 92 / Supreme court refuses Citibank appeal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE US supreme court yesterday refused to overturn a ruling that US banks
can be held responsible for deposits in their foreign branches, even when
those deposits are frozen by a foreign government, writes George Graham.
The court refused to hear an appeal by Citibank, the New York banking group,
against an appeal court ruling that it must repay with interest a Dollars 2m
(Pounds 1.08m) deposit made in Manila in 1983 by the Singapore branch of
Wells Fargo Bank, even though the Philippine government had frozen the
deposits of all foreign banks.
Citibank's appeal had been backed by the Bush administration, which argued
in a submission to the supreme court that the appeal court decision would
create 'new and unforeseeable liabilities' for US banks 'arising from the
unpredictable actions of foreign governments'. Mr Kenneth Starr, the
solicitor general, argued that US banks should be held liable in such cases
only if the two parties had specifically agreed in advance that the home
office should bear responsibility.
Citibank said yesterday it would be discussing with bank regulatory agencies
whether legislative or regulatory changes might be needed to deal with the
consequences of the decision. It would also be discussing with other
international banks the possibility of expanding deposit documentation to
cover the issue of head office liability.
</TEXT>
