FT  23 JUN 92 / Algerian subsidy removal cuts import bill
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANCIS GHILES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   A WEEKEND decision by Algeria to remove subsidies from foodstuffs
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
with the exception of bread, semolina and milk, for which subsidies have
been halved - is expected to save the country Dollars 500m (Pounds 270m)
worth of imports or a quarter of its total foreign food bill in a full year
as consumption patterns are changed. Food imports have accounted for a
quarter of all Algerian imports. This year's savings are expected to amount
to around Dollars 150m.
The decision by the government of Mr Sid Ahmed Ghozali removes a big hurdle
in discussions with the International Monetary Fund, with which Algeria is
negotiating its third standby credit since 1989.
It will also comfort western creditors, in particular Italy and Japan, which
have encouraged lenders to refinance Algerian state or commercial bank debt
as a gesture of support for reforms aimed at liberalising the country's
economy.
The move will halve the cost of food subsidies, which would have amounted to
AD52bn (Pounds 1.3bn) this year. The 7.4m poorest Algerians, out of a
population of 25m, will be spared the worst, as a safety net, which by all
accounts is working reasonably well, introduced welfare payments to them
three months ago.
The liberalisation will end the large black market in commodities such as
sugar, coffee and dairy products conducted with Morocco and Tunisia, where
prices on such products have been much higher than in Algeria for years.
</TEXT>
