FT  23 JUN 92 / UN close to Iraq oil deal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ERIC FREY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   VIENNA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
UN AND Iraqi delegates yesterday reached tentative agreement on a limited
resumptions of Iraqi oil exports solely for humanitarian purposes after six
months of protracted negotiations.
The accord would permit Iraq to export about Dollars 1.6bn worth of oil over
a six-months' period, Mr Giandomenico Picco, the United Nations
undersecretary and chief negotiator told reporters.
'I think that almost all the technical issues have been cleared up,' he
said. He did not disclose technical details or conditions in the settlement,
which has to be approved by the UN Security Council and the Iraqi
government.
A full economic embargo imposed on Iraq after its invasion of Kuwait in
August 1990 bars any oil sales not specifically authorised by the UN
Security Council.
If accepted, the pact would represent a significant concession by the
Iraqis, who have so far rejected any agreement that would impose limits and
conditions on their oil exports.
