<HEADLINE>
FT  23 JUN 92 / Tokyo stock market plunges
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEFAN WAGSTYL and EMIKO TERAZONO
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
JAPANESE shares plunged yesterday as investors lost faith in the
government's willingness to act quickly to stimulate the country's flagging
economy.
The Nikkei average of leading stocks fell 598.65 to 15,921.22, the first
time it has finished below 16,000 since October 1986.
The fall added to nervousness in London over the sluggishness of the main
world economies, and the FT-SE index closed almost 35 points down at
2,550.3. In New York, however, leading US stocks rebounded to close with
modest losses after declining more than 30 points at one stage on the back
of the depressed markets in Japan and Britain. The Dow Jones industrial
average ended off 4.55 at 3,280.80.
In Tokyo today, stocks weakened further in hesitant early trading and the
Nikkei had fallen by nearly 50 points.
Yesterday, when the bear market plumbed new depths, brokers were unable to
forecast how much further stocks might fall. Mr Jason James, an analyst at
James Capel, the UK-based securities company, said: 'There are chances that
the 15,000 level for the Nikkei will hold. But, on the other hand, there
really isn't a reason why it should.'
Mr Tatsuhiko Kusuzawa, a senior managing director at Yamaichi Securities,
said: 'The private sector cannot do anything. Everything now depends on what
kind of fiscal and monetary boost the authorities can implement.'
The government gave no clear indication of its plans, undermining the
impression given last Friday that ruling Liberal Democratic party officials
were forcing the cautious Ministry of Finance into advancing plans for
increased government spending.
Mr Kiichi Miyazawa, the prime minister, said at a press conference marking
the end of a session of the Diet that the economy was now the Japanese
people's main concern. However, he made no specific commitments to take
action to stimulate the economy.
Mr Tsutomu Hata, the finance minister, ruled out action to resuscitate the
stock market through immediate measures, such as increases in public works
spending. But behind the scenes LDP officials are lobbying with increasing
intensity for an extra spending package of up to Y5,000bn (Pounds 21bn) to
Y8,000bn.
The stock market's fall below 16,000 has cut into the value of securities
holdings of big financial institutions, including banks and life assurance
companies. Mr Nobuhiro Kaneda, a general manager at Daiwa Securities, the
stockbroker, estimated that the Nikkei's drop would lead to some banks
having difficulty in meeting international standards of capital adequacy set
by the Bank for International Settlements.
Foreign successes, Page 21
Government bonds, Page 29
World stocks, Page 37
</TEXT>
