<HEADLINE>
FT  23 JUN 92 / De Klerk halts trip as ANC calls crisis talks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP GAWITH
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JOHANNESBURG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SOUTH AFRICAN president FW de Klerk decided yesterday to cut short a visit
to Spain and return home in time to chair a cabinet meeting tomorrow on the
country's political turmoil.
His change of plan follows a decision by the African National Congress -
which on Sunday cut off bilateral talks with the government - to convene an
emergency national executive committee meeting today.
The ANC, which accused Mr de Klerk of insensitivity in leaving the country
at this time, will discuss its response to last week's massacre of 42 people
at Boipatong, near Johannesburg.
It blames the attack on the Zulu-based Inkatha movement, and is incensed
that three more people were killed on Saturday by police who opened fire on
a crowd soon after Mr de Klerk aborted a visit to the township.
The ANC, is expected either to suspend temporarily its participation in the
Convention for a Democratic South Africa (Codesa) - the constitutional
negotiating forum made up of 19 political parties - or to make further
participation dependent on the government's response to the massacre.
South African financial markets reacted nervously yesterday to the
deteriorating political mood. Worst affected was the financial rand, the
investment currency for foreigners, which fell by 6.7 per cent from Friday's
close to finish at R3.84 to the dollar. The discount to the commercial rand
widened to 27 per cent, the highest this year.
On the Johannesburg Stock Exchange, the overall index closed at 3,639, down
42 points.
This is the worst crisis in South Africa's negotiation process since the
unbanning of the ANC in February 1990. But there were hints from both sides
that they may be seeking to pull back from the brink. Mr Tertius Delport,
the government's spokesman on Codesa, said it would be a 'tragedy' if the
ANC was to pull out of the forum.
Mr Delport said an invitation to the ANC by Mr Pik Botha, foreign minister
and acting president in Mr de Klerk's absence, to join the government in
talks was an effort to move forward.
Professor Kadar Asmal, a member of the ANC executive, said the organisation
was 'firmly committed' to negotiations, but added the way out of the impasse
was to move quickly to an interim government.
Britain urged all sides to return to the negotiating table. Mr John Major,
the prime minister, was said to be 'very distressed' at the events.
Editorial comment, Page 18
World stocks, Page 37
</TEXT>
