FT  23 JUN 92 / International Company News: Nestle increases presence in
Asia
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SIMON HOLBERTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   HONG KONG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
NESTLE, the Swiss food manufacturer, said yesterday it intended to pay
HKDollars 1.5bn (USDollars 194m) for 51 per cent of the manufacturing assets
in Hong Kong and southern China of Dairy Farm International, the Hong
Kong-based international food retailer.
Dairy Farm said it would sell a controlling stake in its wholly-owned Hong
Kong dairy products manufacturer as well as control of its 70 per cent-owned
Guangzhou (Canton) ice cream maker, Guangzhou Refrigerated Foods.
The deal, which is expected to be concluded in October, marks Nestle's first
move into food manufacture in the colony and increases its presence in
mainland China.
The Swiss company also plans to buy the Jardine Matheson-controlled Dairy
Farm's brand names.
The two companies said they would establish a joint venture company to make
and distribute ice cream and chilled products, such as milk and yoghurt, in
Hong Kong and China.
Mr Chris Nelson, managing director of Dairy Farm, said the company had been
looking for a partner for some time to help develop the possibilities for
large-scale food manufacture now available in China.
'We have been getting so many approaches from other cities and provinces in
China but we did not have the resources to meet the demands,' Mr Nelson
added.
The cash released to Dairy Farm by the sale will allow it to develop further
its retailing operations in Hong Kong, Britain, Spain, Australasia, China
and Taiwan.
The deal also marks a further retreat by Dairy Farm from manufacturing to
distribution and retailing.
For Nestle, the deal adds a consumer food manufacturer to its other two main
manufacturing interests in China.
In Heilongjiang, in north-east China, it makes infant foods and full-cream
milk powder; in Dongguan, south of Guangzhou, it has China's largest instant
coffee manufacturing plant.
Mr K. F. Lim, Nestle's chief in Hong Kong, said the purchase of Dairy Farm's
assets strengthened the company's position in Hong Kong.
The turnover of its two businesses in China was greater than Dairy Farm's in
China, he added.
Mr Lim said the potential of the Chinese market was great. Although it was
false to look at it in terms of China's population of 1.2bn people, in the
coastal provinces of the country there were between 300m and 400m people
with money and the relative freedom of choice.
'When an economy reaches a certain stage as has China's, people can afford
the luxury of choice,' he said.
'It is then that products such as ice cream come into their own. We believe
there is considerable room for growth in China.'
</TEXT>
