<HEADLINE>
FT  23 JUN 92 / UK Company News: Hays in Pounds 38m French acquisition
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD GOURLAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HAYS, the business services group, yesterday announced a long sought move
into Europe through the acquisition of a French food and drink distribution
company financed by a Pounds 34.3m placement of shares.
The company is paying Pounds 37.5m for Groupe FRIL, a private distributor of
drinks and chilled foods for customers that include Carrefour, Yoplait and
Moet Hennessy. Hays could pay an additional Pounds 15m over three years,
depending on FRIL's profits.
Mr Ronnie Frost, chairman and chief executive, said Hays had been wanting to
expand in Europe for 18 months and that the FRIL acquisition would be
followed by one in the commercial services area in France or Germany.
After yesterday's placing, the group's balance sheet was in good shape to
make further acquisitions without issuing any more new paper.
Gearing had fallen from 30 per cent to 26 per cent on net debt of Pounds
38m. 'There are a lot of good acquisition targets out there in Europe and
England,' Mr Frost said. 'I am in an acquisitive mood.'
He said FRIL would enhance the company's earnings, previously forecast at
12.3p in 1992-93, to about 12.6p. The acquisition would deliver earnings
equivalent to 18p for each of the 19m new Hays shares being issued.
FRIL had sales of FF450 (Pounds 45m) in the year to September 1991 from its
three trading groups - Logistique Barre, Transports Barre and TAC
Developpement. It made operating profits of FF48m before interest, tax and
start up losses on new contracts.
Hays is buying net assets revalued last September at Pounds 7m and is also
assuming FF250m of FRIL's debt.
Since Mr Frost brought Hays to the market in 1989, two years after a
management buy-out from the Kuwait Investment Office, the company's market
capitalisation has almost doubled to Pounds 723m. But the company has
remained almost totally dependent on the UK economy.
Mr Frost said FRIL provided a platform to widen Hays' geographical spread.
'Hays' existing activities in distribution, together with those of FRIL,
will be able to offer continental European customers the type of services
that they are beginning to demand.'
Schroders underwrote and Rowe &amp; Pitman placed the shares yesterday morning
at 182p with a range of institutions. Hays share price closed down 3p at
187p.
Mr Frost said there continued to be no evidence of economic recovery in the
UK. The personnel division - the third business area which supplies
specialised people - remained flat. When the recession came to an end,
however, it would recover very quickly and about 70 per cent of its billings
would go straight to the bottom line, he said.
</TEXT>
